\chapter*{About Sanskrit grammar}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Genders}

Sanskrit has three genders.

\begin{itemize}

\item The male gender is {\dn pu.mli"ngam} = pu.mli"ngam, which
  literally means ``male gender'':

  \begin{itemize}

  \item \note{\noun, \male, {\dn puru.sa.h} = puru.sa.h = male}

  \item \note{\noun, \neuter, {\dn li"ngam} = li"ngam = penis; gender; sign}

  \end{itemize}

\item The female gender is {\dn striili"ngam} = striili"ngam, which
  literally means ``female gender'':

  \begin{itemize}

  \item \note{\noun, \female, {\dn strii} = strii = woman; female; wife}

  \item \note{\noun, \neuter, {\dn li"ngam} = li"ngam = penis; gender; sign}

  \end{itemize}

\item The neuter gender is {\dn napu.msakali"ngam} =
  napu.msakali"ngam, which literally means ``neuter gender'':

  \begin{itemize}

  \item \note{\noun, \neuter, {\dn napu.msakam} = napu.msakam = neuter gender}

  \item \note{\noun, \neuter, {\dn li"ngam} = li"ngam = penis; gender; sign}

  \end{itemize}

\end{itemize}

Nouns have genders. Adjectives have genders. Verbs sometimes have
genders.
% ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Letters}

The writing system of Sanskrit is Devanagari:

\begin{quote}
  \note{\noun, \female, {\dn devanaagarii} = devanaagarii}
\end{quote}

In Devanagari, the letters are syllables---when you pronounce each
letter, you are pronouncing a vowel, or a consonant, followed by a
vowel. (We ignore the two following special letters: {\dn a.m} = a.m
and {\dn a.h} = a.h.)

The pronunciation of some letters is a consonant, followed by a
vowel. Such a letter will sometimes have a special stroke called a
virama ({\dn viraama} = viraama):

\begin{quote}
  \note{\noun, \male, {\dn viraama.h} = viraama.h = pause; stop; end}
\end{quote}

A viraama indicates that the vowel is not to be pronounced. A viraama
looks like a backslash (the character $\backslash$) at the bottom
right of the letter. Examples:

\begin{itemize}

  \item Without viraama: {\dn ka} = ka. With viraama: {\dn k} = k.

  \item Without viraama: {\dn kha} = kha. With viraama: {\dn kh} = kh.

\end{itemize}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Verbs}

In Sanskrit, a verb ``tense'' is called a {\dn lakaara} = lakaara:

\begin{quote}
  \note{\noun, \male, {\dn lakaara.h} = lakaara.h = tense}
\end{quote}

However, a Sanskrit ``tense'' is not exactly the same as an English
tense---a Sanskrit ``tense'' can be an English tense, or an English
mood.

Simply, a tense is a form of a verb that shows time, and a mood is a
form of a verb that shows how the speaker feels about something.

Sanskrit has ten verb ``tenses,'' below. Other people may list them in
different orders.\\

\begin{tabular}{llll}
  Verb tense or mood&Sanskrit&Transliteration&Informal description\\
  \hline
  &&\\
  present tense&{\dn la.t}&la.t&I walk.\\
  &&\\
  past tense (imperfect)&{\dn la"n}&la"n&I have walked.\\
  &&\\
  past tense (aorist)&{\dn lu"n}&lu"n&I did something with walking.\\
  &&\\
  past tense (perfect)&{\dn li.t}&li.t&I had walked.\\
  &&\\
  future tense (possibly)&{\dn lu.t}&lu.t&I may walk.\\
  &&\\
  future tense (certain)&{\dn l.r.t}&l.r.t&I will walk.\\
  &&\\
  conditional mood&{\dn l.r"n}&l.r"n&If I go, then I would walk.\\
  &&\\
  potential mood&{\dn vidhili"n}&vidhili"n&I can walk. I might walk.\quad\dots\\
  &&&(can; could; may; might; should; would)\\
  &&\\
  benedictive mood&{\dn a"siirli"n}&a"siirli"n&I want to walk. I wish to walk.\\
  &&\\
  imperative mood&{\dn lo.t}&lo.t&Walk! Let's walk!\\
\end{tabular}

\begin{itemize}

\item Verbs about yourself are called {\dn aatmanepada} = aatmanepada,
  which literally means ``self word'':

  \begin{itemize}

  \item \note{\noun, \male, {\dn aatmaa} = aatmaa = self}

  \item \note{\noun, \neuter, {\dn padam} = padam = foot; step; word}

  \end{itemize}

  For these verbs, the doer of the action is also the receiver.

  People might call these verbs ``reflexive verbs.''

\item Verbs about others are called {\dn parasmaipada} = parasmaipada,
  which literally means ``other word'':

  \begin{itemize}

  \item \note{\adjective, {\dn para} = para = other; another}

  \item \note{\noun, \neuter, {\dn padam} = padam = foot; step; word}

  \end{itemize}

  For these verbs, the doer of the action is not the receiver of the
  action.

\item Verbs about both yourself and others are called {\dn ubhayapada}
  = ubhayapada, which literally means ``both word'':

  \begin{itemize}

  \item \note{\adjective, {\dn ubhaya} = ubhaya = both; two}

  \item \note{\noun, \neuter, {\dn padam} = padam = foot; step; word}

  \end{itemize}

  For these verbs, the doer of the action can be the receiver of the
  action, but it does not have to be.

\end{itemize}

Each verb has a ``root.'' A verb form has the following parts:

\begin{enumerate}

\item Prefix, which can be nothing.

\item Root, called a {\dn dhaatu} = dhaatu:

  \begin{quote}
    \note{\noun, \male, {\dn dhaatu.h} = dhaatu.h = verb root; ingredient; component}
  \end{quote}

\item Infix, called a {\dn vikara.napratyaya.h} = vikara.napratyaya.h,
  which literally means ``change affix'':

  \begin{itemize}

  \item \note{\noun, \neuter, {\dn vikara.nam} = vikara.nam = change}

  \item \note{\noun, \male, {\dn pratyaya.h} = pratyaya.h = affix}

  \end{itemize}

\item Suffix, called a {\dn ti"npratyaya.h} = ti"npratyaya.h.

  \begin{itemize}

  \item \note{{\dn ti"n} = ti"n = (?)}

  \item \note{\noun, \male, {\dn pratyaya.h} = pratyaya.h = affix}

  \end{itemize}

\end{enumerate}
