\section*{Plurals}

Sanskrit has three plurals.\\

\begin{tabular}{llll}
  1&singular&{\dn ekavacanam}&\transliteration{ekavacanam} (``one word'')\\
  2&dual&{\dn dvivacanam}&\transliteration{dvivacanam} (``two word'')\\
  3&plural&{\dn bahuvacanam}&\transliteration{bahuvacanam} (``many word'')\\
\end{tabular}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{``Persons''}

Sanskrit has three ``persons.'' A ``person'' is called a {\dn
  puru.sa.h} = puru.sah = man. The persons are the reverse of the
persons in English.\\

\begin{tabular}{lllllll}
  1&English first person&{\dn uttama.h}&=&uttama.h&=&last\\
  2&English second person&{\dn madhyama.h}&=&madhyama.h&=&middle\\
  3&English third person&{\dn prathama.h}&=&prathama.h&=&first\\
\end{tabular}
