\section*{Second-person pronoun: you}

In Sanskrit, many of the second-person words are similar to the
first-person words. Sometimes the only difference is the start of the
word.

In Sanskrit, some of the second-person words start with ``yu'' or
``yuu,'' which sound like the English word ``you.'' In addition, these
sounds sound like the words for ``you'' in some versions of Spanish:
``Usted'' or ``Ustedes.''

If you know languages such as Spanish, French, or Italian, you may
find it interesting that Sanskrit uses ``t'' at the start of some
singular second-person words, like those languages. Also, Sanskrit
uses ``v'' at the start of some dual or plural second-person words,
