\subsection*{Third-person pronouns: one/which}

For the third-person pronouns ``one/which,'' you can get their cases
from the cases for ``that'' by replacing the first letter by
``y''. For example:

\begin{itemize}

\item Male: {\dn sa.h} = sa.h = that/he. {\dn ya.h} = ya.h =
  one/which.

\item Female: {\dn saa} = saa = that/she. {\dn yaa} = yaa = one/which.

\item Neuter: {\dn tat} = tat = that/it. {\dn yat} = yat = one/which.

\end{itemize}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection*{Third-person pronouns: what/who}

For the third-person pronouns ``what/who,'' you can get their cases
from the cases for ``that'' by replacing the first letter by
``k''. For example:

\begin{itemize}

\item Male: {\dn sa.h} = sa.h = that/he. {\dn ka.h} = ka.h = what/who.

\item Female: {\dn saa} = saa = that/she. {\dn kaa} = kaa = what/who.

\end{itemize}

However, there are two small exceptions to this ``replace by k'' rule:
for the neuter cases, the nominative singular and accusative singular
are not {\dn kat} = kat, but they are {\dn kim} = kim.
